result.execSummary:
The defendant Derrick M Parker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Grams.  Victim notification not needed.  No victim response to DA's office.  Defendant plead no contest to Count 2.  Count 1, dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court recited the charge and possible penalties on the counts he plead to.  Defendant understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his pleas and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Crimimal Damage to Property, contrary to 943.01(1).  State requesting a fine of $50.00 plus costs.  Court ordered same.  Pay @ $50.00 per month, starting 2/1/17.    Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.    Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.
